As you walk in, a bell on the door gives a pleasant jingle.\n\n[img[cashier]]\n\nHello says the middle aged man at the register. Can I help you with anything? He listens intently as you give your impassioned speech. Honestly, I cant afford to have my store affiliated with any political parties. Could lose me customers. But I myself agree completely. You have my personal support. The owner signs the petition and pockets a Independents party pin. With a smile you leave the quaint little store. At least youve got one more persons support.. A small victory.\n\t\n[[Next|6]]\n\n<<set $strategist = $strategist + 1>>
As you walk in the doors, you see stacks of well-organized, high end home decor. You walk up to the front desk and give your speech with extra vigor.\n\nNothing I can do with this, but I can take your information down and hand it off to my manager, the woman at the desk says in a dry tone, Hell be in tomorrow.\n\nThank you, you force a smile and pretend not to be disappointed as you walk out the door. Even more discouraged, you press on to find more recruits.\n\n[[Next|6]]\n\n<<set $philanthropist = $philanthropist + 1>>
A few days later, after drawing up a petition opposing Hangeros imperialistic influence, you and some of the the Independents group disperse throughout the city and take signatures and recruit members. The canvassers have a memorized script to sound professional introducing their cause. There is hope that the community will support it.\nThough you try to talk to everyone you see, most of them just ignore you and go about their day. Why would they be so apathetic? Perhaps they are too afraid to speak their mind. Or maybe you are one in few who support the cause. Either way, you need to start focusing on convincing people. \nIts not just about getting the message out anymore. You need scope out people who you can and need to bring into the movement. The street begins to empty. With no one else to walk up to, you need to start seeking people out.\n\n[[You notice an attorney's office down the street. Maybe someone in law could be reasonable and influential.|4_1]]\n\n[[You notice a medical office on the corner. You walk in hoping to find any caring supporters.|4_2]]\n\n
[img[doctor]]\nA well groomed man in a lab coat walks idly by looking over a clipboard. As he looks up to greet you, you immediately extend your arm to shake the doctors hand.\n\nHello, I wanted to talk to you about the social conflicts that the Independents party are trying to address and how you may help. You give the usual speech about raising awareness for imperialistic tendencies, and how they can affect the countries involved. Then you make it more personal.\n\nTo be honest, our group could really use someone with your kind of notoriety. Educated, hard-working, and a respected helper of the community. I want to invite you to come to join us to try to make Pazonia a better place.\n\n[[Next|5]]\n\n<<set $philanthropist = $philanthropist + 1>>\n<<set $strategist = $strategist + 1>>
Thinking Makes It So
[img[suit]]\n\nA well dressed man adjusts his silk tie in the mirror of his opened office. As he looks up to greet you, you immediately extend your arm to shake the lawyers hand.\n\nHello, I wanted to talk to you about the social conflicts that the Independents party are trying to address and how you may help. You give the usual speech about raising awareness for imperialistic tendencies, and how they can affect the countries involved. Then you make it more personal.\n\nTo be honest, our group could really use someone with your kind of notoriety. Educated, clever, and an influential member of the community. The guards leave the room. You take a seat in front of the man and stare into his eyes for a moment. \n\nI dont know anything, I swear! The man says.\n\nYoure going to tell me who you work for, you say calmly.\n\nI dont work for anyone! Im just a member of the commune!\n\nWell, here what we lack in resources, we make up for in organization. Since weve had to ration our supplies, we have kept very good track of people who live here. Where do you live?\n\nUnit B13, he says with panic in his voice.\n\nYou pull out a list from the offices files. According to our records unit B13 has been empty for a while. No rations going in. Now, you look well fed. You must have had someone else feeding you.\n\nHis face changes to a cool expression as if he is daring you to make a move. \n\nWhats your name? you ask. The mans eyes narrow and he remains silent. You hit him hard with the back of your hand. He licks his bleeding lip.\n\nWhy dont you just call me Troy, He says with a sneer.\n\nDo you know what happened Troy?\n\nSimple enough. Your friend go boom, His smile makes your blood boil. You take him by the hair.\n\nYoure going to tell me why.\n\nWhy should I? We both know youre going to kill me anyway.\n\nIm not going to kill you. You let go of his hair and head over to a desk. You take a pencil out from a drawer and break it half. Calmly, you go back to Troy and take his tied hand in your own. The pencil has broken into a fine point that is just sharp enough to fit under his nail. He struggles, but your will is powerful.\n\nHe grits his teeth and holds back a scream. You sit back down in front of him. Who do you work for? He breathes heavily and glares at you. You go back to his hand and use the extra rope to tie his fingers down. This time, you use the broken pencil with more force.\n\nTroy screams in agony. Hangero! He yells almost intelligibly. He lets out a frustrated yell.\n\nWhat did you do here, Troy? the wood still under his nail, you press harder.\n\nAaaaaah-I-I activated The bomb, Please! Stop! You pay no attention to his request. Blood drips down from his hand.\n\nYou shout over his cries. Why did you activate it? How did you know he had it?\n\nI geeaaaaah! I worked as aaaaaaah spy in Canteraaaaaa! Goooodaaaamnit!! I knew they gave you explosives, and I- aaaaah! You let back a bit so he can have time to speak, but he becomes silent again. Tears streak down his face. You take him by the hair again and stick the pencil half an inch from his eye. His voice is shaky and panicked. We wanted to destroy your weapons and offices! Hangero wants to bring you down! We knew your Captain would arm the explosives, so I rewired the bomb to my detonator!\n\nThank you, you say in a calm voice. You put the bloody pencil on the desk and leave the room. Keep him under guard, you tell a soldier without looking him in the eye.\n\n[[Next |A34]]\n\n<<set $militant = $militant + 1>>\n

[img[sad]]\n\nThe rest of your party head home with the disappointing supplies provided by Cantera. Upon arrival at Fort Ally, you find things in worse shape than when you left. Food is scarce, people are afraid, and there is a Hangeroan camp set up just a few miles away from the commune. It is clear that Canteras supplies will do very little to help. \n\nWord from Cantera arrives that Nilati will not help. Out of options, you beg Nilati for any kind of assistance, but to no avail.\n\nHarold sits in a room with you, his head in his hands. We cant turn to anyone else. All the other Aporan villages are hostile.\n\nAnd Hangero is practically taking over all of Pazonia, you respond while staring at the floor. I thought the Pazonian people were on our side. How could they let this happen?\nHarold gets up and paces the room. Were fucked! He kicks a chair to the wall. The charismatic young man seems to have aged 30 years in just a few months. His eyes are bloodshot and his hair streaked with silver.\n\n<<display "Choices">>\n\n<<set $choice1 = 0>>\n<<set $choice2 = 0>>
[img[village]]\n\nDue to the uncertainty of Canteras loyalty, you take many bodyguards and assistants with you to Cantera. The air is tense as you enter the small village. The party of delegates enters the quaint building used for Canteras business affairs.\n\nWe wish to become your allies, says the leader of the village. We arent many in number, but with our combined forces, we could still fight back against Hangero. We will try to convince Nilati to join us. They have more weapons and supplies than us, and if we three could become united, we would have better chances. What Cantera needs is military assistance. We dont have enough recruits to accomplish anything on our own. What can we offer you for the aid of your soldiers?\n\n\n[[Well need weapons. Our militia is ill equipped to handle our own safety, let alone the safety of Cantera."|A2Q2C1]]\n\n[[Well need food and medical supplies. We need to care for whats left of Fort Ally."|A2Q2C2]]
Prologue\n[img[Map]]\n \nOn the brink of war, your beloved home country, Pazonia is faced with discord. Your neighboring country, Aporanistan, desperately wishes to take advantage of Pazonias oil reserves, but with little in return. The embargo of Aporanistans goods will pressure them into giving Pazonia fair payment for its oil since Pazonia is Aporanistans closest partner in trade. Aporanistan is a country in turmoil and debt, and their desperate attempts to stay afloat become frightening. Pazonia, being a humble country, cannot afford to sell their oil at such a low price, so their main buyer is the country of Hangero. Hangero is a highly militant country, more powerful than Pazonia and Aporanistan combined. Seeing the unrest between the two countries, Hangero steps in with a blunt approach. But soon enough, they begin to show signs of imperialism on both Pazonia and Aporanistan.\n\n[[Next |Act I]]\n\n<<set $strategist = 0>>\n<<set $opportunist = 0>>\n<<set $philanthropist = 0>>\n<<set $pacifist = 0>>\n<<set $assertive = 0>>\n<<set $militant = 0>>

We cannot afford to be exposed. Anyone who gets discovered is left behind.\n\nYes, sir, you respond.\n\nHarold puts his hand on your shoulder and gives a small nod.\n\nOnly you, Harold, and the group tasked with stealing supplies knows about the plan. When they come back, there are no questions asked. The small bit of supplies cant even compare to what Cantera gave. But most importantly, Fort Ally is not to be discovered as the thief.\n\nStill troubled, but not suspected, Fort ally is simply trying to survive. The leaders havent yet had to resort to violence. It would practically be suicide to instigate anything at the moment. Limited supplies meant hardly a chance of defending themselves, let alone making any offensive strikes.\n\nYou walk through the streets of Fort Ally in a dazed state. People try to tend to crops and livestock to have some source of food. All the people in the commune have a thin, gaunt look about them. Many looked as if they were losing the will to live. Although they wanted to leave, they feared Hangeros presence in the rest of the country.\n\nA loud explosion at the edge of the Fort stops you in your tracks. Then we have an agreement, says the leader of Cantera. You leave some of your men here to protect us, we will give you supplies.\n\nThe deal is made, although the amount of supplies Cantera provides is less than sufficient. The store is limited to about a 30 days worth of rations at best. You leave some of your men here to protect us, we will give you supplies.\n\n[img[Weapons]]\n\nThe deal is made, although the amount of weapons Cantera provides is less than sufficient. Kelly Jensen\nGerardo Hernandez\nConor Chibnall\nRoyce Bacon\nLauren Cunningham\nAustin Benyo\nJesse Brownell\nAlex Barrick\nConnor Phillips\n
A crew of your people go out into the commune and try to find any scrap of evidence. You sit on a rock near the place of impact. The area has only two sets of footprints; yours from today, and Harolds from his last steps. They head towards the charred earth from the explosion, then away from it. It seems as if Harold saw something, then tried to run away. He did get some distance before the detonation, but the force brought a shabby brick wall crashing down on top of him. His face is unrecognizable. His informal grave lays on the outskirts of the commune. It isnt good enough for him. But Fort Ally doesnt have the resources for a proper funeral.\nVoices from towards the commune break your troubled contemplation.\n\nCaptain, we have a witness! cries someone from the investigation party. You and the group go back to the leaders offices. An older woman sits, waiting for you.\nI saw Captain Munts before he Begins the woman. There was someone going up to his room. I dont think Ive seen this man before. He wasnt one of the leaders. I thought it was strange, but I didnt think to intrude on the Captains affairs. I thought the man had some business with the him. The man seemed hurried when he left, like he knew something was going to happen. I saw Captain Munts head up to his room normally. He came out with a suitcase. He was running out of the commune. Looked like he was running away.\n\nWhy would Harold just pack up his stuff and run away? Then it dawns on you that no one has checked his room. You have been too distraught to go through any of his things, but maybe they would give you more clues.\n\n[[You look at the woman, Youre going to identify him, you demand. You turn towards the search party. Tear the fort apart if you have to. Find him. |A31a]]\n\n[[You turn towards the woman. Maam, could you identify this man if you saw him again? Ill need you to help my soldiers find him, alright?. |A31b]]\n\n<<set $militant = $militant + 1>>
A crew of your people go out into the commune and try to find any scrap of evidence. You sit on a rock near the place of impact. The area has only two sets of footprints; yours from today, and Harolds from his last steps. They head towards the charred earth from the explosion, then away from it. It seems as if Harold saw something, then tried to run away. He did get some distance before the detonation, but the force brought a shabby brick wall crashing down on top of him. Thinking Makes It So\n\nWe strongly encourage you to think about the choices presented throughout this story, and make the ones that make the most sense to you as a person.\n\n[[When you're ready, you may begin the story.|prologue]]

[img[fall]]\n\nYou look around in a daze to see what has happened. You fall to the ground. [[What did my life mean?]] You think to yourself. Everything goes black.
Nauseated and breathless, you head back to your office.\n\nThe next morning, your soldiers inform you that Troy had escaped. It was bound to happen with Fort Allys lack of a proper jail cell. But your soldiers seem even more incompetent than you thought. After all, they are not real soldiers. They werent trained. They hardly even volunteered for the job. \n\nJust like you, they were forced into this position. \n\nWith Troy gone, Hangero would soon know that youre aware of their animosity. Now your only option is to fight.\n\n[[Organize the troops. We will launch an attack on the Hangeroan camp tomorrow. |A35a]]\n\n[[Make a perimeter around the colony. There is a Young Independents party meeting tonight, you should come, Before you respond, the charismatic boy continues, Were a group of students trying to raise awareness of the imperialistic tendencies of Hangero and to fight to keep Pazonian independence.\n\n[[Yeah, Im not sure my uncle would appreciate that when he practically worships Hangero, you say with an exasperated laugh.|2_1]]\n\n[[I really hate that my uncle practically worshiped Hangero out there. Ill definitely come.|2_2]]
After several more days of canvassing, you and your fellow young Independents have a decent amount of signatures and several more followers.\n\nWe still dont have the publicity we need to actually change the governments minds, Harolds words burn with passion. We need to make them know all about us. We did get a few peoples attention, and I want to congratulate you all on that. But what Im thinking now is a rally! A public demonstration.\n\nThe growing congregation of Independents hang on his every word. He has so much drive for this cause. He clearly knows how to recruit. He alone must have gotten at least thirty percent of all the signatures out of the whole group. If he were to lead a rally, theres no way it would go unnoticed.\n\n[img[protest]]\n\nA week later, the rally takes place in the downtown business district. More people than you ever thought would now come together as a message of Pazonias strength. Several hundred at least follow Harold as he shouts into a megaphone.\nPazonia the free! Pazonia the strong! Pazonia forever! He leads the march out through the crowded street. Cars are backed up behind the line of protesters. Several police try to corral people out of the line of traffic. People stumble in excitement. An officer pushes his way through the crowd towards Harold. They begin speaking with one another. You cant hear what they are saying over the roar of the crowd, but their words are clearly heated. You make your way over to Harolds aid. The officer puts his hand on Harolds chest keeping him at a distance.\n\n[[In a heated attempt to protect Harold, you grab the police mans arm and violently wrench it away.|6_1]]\n\n[[You pull Harold back to make sure the officer does not hurt him.|6_2]]\n\n

Right then. We cant take in the refugees from Pobreso. Too risky. We need to concentrate on helping our own people here, says Harold. The majority of the other leaders nod in agreement.\n\nLittle did they all know that this action would have very negative repercussions. As soon as the word gets out that the leaders wont take in refugees from Aporanistan, many people leave the commune. There is a large portion of people who consider your refusal to be insensitive. The Independents are supposed to be a party for those who want dignity and peace for everyone, after all. Ultimately, Hangero is the enemy, and Aporanistan is just caught in the middle\n\nRecovering from heavy losses, Fort Allys leaders are running out of ideas. With the remains of the Aporan village of Pobreso in ruins at Hangeros hand, the closest Aporan villages to Fort Ally are Nilati and Cantera. Despite your lack of support to Pobreso, Cantera seeks out Fort Allys aid and organizes a diplomatic meeting with you, Harold and the village's leaders.\n\n[[Next|A2Passage1]]\n\n<<set $strategist = $strategist + 1>>\n<<set $assertive = $assertive + 1>>
Harold thinks for a moment. I guess youre right. We could use more allies in government. If we cant persuade the leaders of our own country, why not try Aporanistan? The majority of the other leaders nod in agreement.\n\nLittle did they all know that this action would have very negative repercussions. Fort Ally takes in those helpless, homeless victims of Hangeros cruelty, but not all of them are friendly. A small group that came in with the refugees blame the Independents for everything that has happened to Aporanistan. An attack on the commune leaves hundreds of your followers dead in an act of merciless revenge.\n\nRecovering from heavy losses, Fort Allys leaders are running out of ideas. The night of the summit is at hand. At the entrance to the building where the summit is taking place, there is a large crowd of professionally dressed people. Your uncle must be around somewhere, but you dont see him in the immediate vicinity. Many of the diplomats from Hangero, Aporanistan, and Pazonia enter with their bodyguards and assistants. You stand alone with nothing but your new business clothes and a notebook of things to say.\n\nThe security at the summit is very tight. Tensions have obviously been running high everywhere. You step closer to where people are being checked. You wonder how it got this far. You werent supposed to be a huge political figure. That was your uncles job. But you sounded your opinion and here you are, the last thread keeping Pazonia from succoming to complete imperialism.\n\nYou gaze around at the most civilized event youve seen in months. The city is lighted, the roads are paved, and the buildings arent crumbling. You notice a figure on top of one of the elegant buildings. The distant face of Troy peaks out from behind the scope of a rifle. Taken aback, you hear a loud bang.\n\n[img[sniper]]\n\n[[Next |A37]]\n\n<<set $philanthropist = $philanthropist + 1>>\n<<set $pacifist = $pacifist + 1>>
No one needs to know what Harold was doing. Who even knows already? Maybe the bombs were just a failsafe in case of an attack. But they are more suited to make an offensive attack. Suddenly you hear rushed footsteps outside. You close up the suitcase and hide it away before anyone sees. Your soldiers stand at the door both holding a man captive with the woman who witnessed it behind them.\n\nCaptain, this is the man responsible. One of your soldiers says.\n\n[img[tied]]\n\nIt is, this is the man I saw, says the woman. Too livid to say anything, you walk past the group to another office, beckoning them to follow.\n\nThank you, maam, you say calmly to the woman. We no longer need your help. You turn to your other soldiers. Get some rope. We need to keep this man detained.\n\nYour soldiers tie the perpetrator to a chair and keep their scavenged weapons at the ready.\n\n[img[rope]]\n\n[[Leave us. Ill find out what he knows myself. Before you can pull him away from the tension, he violently wrenches the officers arm off his chest. The two begin to brawl. You try your hardest to pull the officer away. He knocks you to the ground as more protesters and officers join the fight.\n\n[[Next|7]]\n\n<<set $pacifist = $pacifist + 1>>
The night of the summit is at hand. At the entrance to the building where the summit is taking place, there is a large crowd of professionally dressed people. Your uncle must be around somewhere, but you dont see him in the immediate vicinity. Many of the diplomats from Hangero, Aporanistan, and Pazonia enter with their bodyguards and assistants. You stand alone with nothing but your new business clothes and a suitcase.\n\nThe security at the summit is very tight. Tensions have obviously been running high everywhere. You step closer to where people are being checked. This is your last chance. You cant take out everyone, but you can make damn sure they know you wouldnt go out as their dog.\n\nYou open the suitcase, hands shaking and fiddle with the wires. There is a very particular technique that you must employ to activate the bomb. You try and be discrete, but your hands are sweating, and the suitcase falls open onto the ground. People gasp and a woman screams. A security guard catches sight of you and points a gun to your back. He should still be here to lead the fort. Instead all of his duties are on you. But Harold was so much better at leading. He came up with the plans. He did all the negotiating. Why did Harold even think of you as his second? He was clearly superior\n\nYou solemnly go through the files on his desk. Some strange blueprints and plans are mixed in with his things in a drawer. You dont have the slightest clue what they are.\n\nThere is a cupboard with broken lock on it in the corner of the room. Why didnt Harold replace the lock right after it broke? You open the cupboard door. A lone black suitcase is inside. You open it up. There are wires and a clock attached to a brick-shaped package. You stumble back in shock. Its a bomb. Harold was carrying a bomb out of the commune. Someone must have planted it there and Harold was trying to save us all.\n\n[img[c4]]\n\nThen you realize that the plans on Harolds desk match the array of wires in the suitcase. Harold made the bombs. Both of them were his.\n\n[[Stupid Harold |A32a]]\n\n[[Poor Harold |A32b]]\n\n<<set $militant = $militant + 1>>

[img[grave]]\n\nYou go back to the outskirts of the fort near Harolds grave. Your mind is blank. You stare, expressionless at the trees beyond the commune's perimeter. We are all monsters here. The only way to get information from that man is to beat it out of him and you know it. And you dont tell your soldiers otherwise.\n\nIn what seems like an eternity, your soldiers come back with small blood splatters on their clothes. One of them somberly tells you the story. He says his name is Troy doesnt sound very believable. He works for Hangero. Said he knew Cantera gave us a few explosives with the supplies. And he found the bomb in Captain Munts room. There were two of them. Munts made them. Did you know about this? He asks with concern.\n\nNo, you respond. Dont let anyone else know either.\n\nThe soldier continues. Well, this Troy guy was trying to blow up the offices by rewiring Harolds bomb to his detonator. Kind of attack us at the heart. So Munts must have realized he couldnt defuse it after Troy had activated it. He took it away from the commune and chucked it. He saved us.\n\nIs Troy still alive? you ask.\n\nYes. But, Captain, I had to...\n\nI dont want to know. Just keep him under guard.\nWithout another word, you get up and walk back to the commune.\n\n[[Next |A34]]\n\n<<set $assertive = $assertive + 1>>\n
[img[d4]]\n\nAfter your stint in jail, public outcry for anti-Hangeroan policies becomes blatant. The issue with police brutality during the riot has made the Pazonian people voice against authoritative figures in government. Worried about opposition, Hangero brings in military units to police the major cities of Pazonia. A small village near Pazonias border to Aporanistan becomes an ideal place for Independents activities and becomes Harolds and your new home. Within a few months, the place becomes a commune and sanctuary for Independents wanting to stay away from Hangeroan forces. Those forces, however, continue to brutalize Aporanistan in an attempt to keep its people from starting any opposition. You and Harold, being heroes who had been jailed for the cause, become two of the leaders of the commune called Fort Ally.\n\nIts only a matter of time before Hangeroan forces seek us out. We practically started the opposition. What we need is the Aporans as allies, says a fellow leader of Fort Ally. We could take in their refugees as an act of good faith. Theres a village in Aporanistan thats almost completely destroyed. I think it was called Pobreso.\n\nHarold contemplates the thought. But can we really trust them? Aporanistan tried to give us the short end in the first place. Plus, our opposition has made Hangero come down on them twice as hard as us. What if they blame us for it all? And I dont even think we can take in any more people. The commune only has so much supplies. Harold looks to hear your opinion.\n\n[[We cant trust them. Harold is right. We dont know if they are hostile or not.|A2Q1C1]] \n\n[[Well, the Aporan people arent war mongerers. Theyve just had some hard times. I think offering our help will show that we still have a common enemy and should therefore unite with eachother.|A2Q1C2]] \n
